benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/invoicePayments/{paymentId}/tags - Remove tags from payment

covered: Valid deletion scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05, TC10) asserting 204 and empty body or unchanged state.
Comprehensive input validation (TC06, TC07, TC08, TC09) covering invalid/absent/missing/invalid tagDef values and non-existent payment.
Header/auth checks (TC08 for missing header, TC11 for unauthorized).
System resilience (TC12) for service unavailability and (TC22) timeout scenario.
Query parameter handling (TC14, TC15) including extra parameters and large numbers of tagDefs.
Concurrency and performance (TC16, TC17) coverage for race conditions and load.
Audit and data integrity (TC20, TC21) coverage.
Backward compatibility and regression coverage (TC19, TC18).
Edge case: removal with no tags (TC05) and removal when tag not present (TC10).
gaps: Authorization: lacks a test for 403 Forbidden / insufficient permissions scenario.
Caching: no tests validating caching headers like ETag or Cache-Control.
Rate limiting: no tests for throttling or rate-limiting behavior.
Soft delete semantics: no explicit tests differentiating hard vs soft delete behavior.
Explicit idempotence test: an isolated test ensuring repeated DELETE calls remain 204 with no adverse effects.
recommendations: Add a 403 Forbidden test to verify proper handling when the user lacks required permissions.
Add tests to validate caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) and potential cache invalidation on deletion.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests under concurrent or bursty DELETE requests.
Add an explicit idempotence test to confirm repeated deletions do not cause errors and state remains consistent (beyond existing no-op cases).
Consider a dedicated test for 204 with extra query parameters in combination with tagDef to ensure no side effects.
Provide a focused test for 403 with invalid authorization token to complement TC11.
